description: Ever wonder why Batman v Superman: Dawn of Justice was so divisive? Step into the pitch meeting that started it all! Subscribe to our channel: http://goo.gl/ho3Hg6 #SuperEasyBarelyAnInconvenienceSo Batman is finally coming to the DCEU, and since his origin story has already been done a million times, they decided to do it again. But this time in super slow motion. So the movie starts off with Batman mad at Superman because while he was fighting Zod, Batman's friend Jack got killed. Lex Luthor then orchestrates a plan to get Batman and Superman to fight each other. But this isn't your typical Lex Luthor. This one is young, has hair, likes candy and makes a lot of funny Mickey Mouse noises. His whole plan is super easy, barely an inconvenience. So Batman and Superman fight for a couple minutes until Batman realizes that Superman has a mom. Then Superman dies fighting Doomsday and we all pretend that he's going to stay dead. tags: the last jedi|star wars|episode 8|snoke|rey|luke|finn|rose|kylo ren|poe|poe dameron|leia|princess leia|death|space|flying|mary popping|pitch|sketch|funny|parody|comedy|force awakens|skywalker|lightsaber
description: If you've seen The Last Jedi, you may be wondering how some of those big decisions were made. Well, take a look inside the pitch meeting to find out! Subscribe to our channel: http://goo.gl/ho3Hg6 The Last Jedi has stormed into theaters. The film is certainly one of the most complex films set in a galaxy far, far away so you’ll be forgiven if you didn’t catch everything on the first viewing. There’s a ton going on in the background that you may not have even noticed and we’re here to help you find them. For example, did you catch that Rey stole the Jedi books? Blink and you’ll miss it! Luke’s final reveal was actually telegraphed well in advanced in a masterful way. Supreme Leader Snoke actually has a piece of bling that harkens back to Rogue One! Speaking of bling, what were those dice that we saw a few times? Luke has a stash of trinkets at the tree on Ahch-To, one of them ties directly to Star Wars Battlefront 2 while another may be a reference to the beloved Knights of the Old Republic video games. We get our first look, sort of, at the first Jedi while at the temple with Luke and Rey. Did you think Rian Johnson forgot about the famous line “I have a bad feeling about this?” Think again! We got to see the old X Wing used in a very interesting way and get a call back to a character from Rogue One in the form of a ship. Of course, being Star Wars, there are a ton of cameos in the film that you likely didn’t catch either, some of them being quite obvious! description: INSTAGRAM : https://www.instagram.com/willfons5Check out our T Shirts: https://teespring.com/stores/will-weeklyINSTAGRAM : WillFons5Facebook: facebook.com/wfonsWebsite: https://willfons.wixsite.com/willfonsThe first weekend of the year, which at its apex in 2016 grossed $219.5M off the heat of Disney’s Star Wars: The Force Awakens, registered an estimated $13M for the entire weekend. That’s in a continued decimated exhibition marketplace that’s praying to reopen in 2021.Warner Bros.’ theatrical release of Wonder Woman 1984, which is also available on HBO Max for the next 21 days, grossed $5.5M, -67%, for a running domestic B.O. of $28.5M. From that kind of drop, it sounds like whatever moviegoing public exists out there finally got the message that they can see the movie at a cheaper price for the family at home on HBO Max. Either that or given the B+ CinemaScore on WW1984, word of mouth has stalled the sequel at the box office, and folks have figured out that it’s more economical for them to watch it at home. Warners has yet to provide hard numerical details on the spike in subscribers or viewership for WW1984 on HBO Max.Related Story'Soul' Jazzy In China While 'Little Red Flower' Blooms With $116M Debut; 'Wonder Woman 1984' Now At $119M Worldwide - International Box OfficeDespite the awful New Year’s weekend, many pics respecting some sort of theatrical window saw weekend-to-weekend gains in their grosses from the previous Christmas 3-day, i.e. Monster Hunter, Fatale, Croods 2, Pinocchio, War With Grandpa, Come Play, or decent holds, i.e. Promising Young Woman and News of the World. Also, showing that some moviegoing habits haven’t changed even with fewer people going, Saturday’s daily box office business for most of the top 10 films was, on average, +11% over Friday.While Warner is banging the drum on the global cume, now at $118.5M, which, let’s face it, would be significantly higher had the studio waited this tentpole out to a healthier time in the marketplace, box office analysts believe the Patty Jenkins movie will fizzle at around $40M in a domestic marketplace where 60% of all 5.5K theaters are closed. Warner’s Tenet, with the No. 2 chain Regal open during the majority of that pic’s run, halted at $57.9M. A reminder that with fewer box office DMAs open, the majors are also holding on their usual tentpole marketing spend.Meanwhile, read the @HBOMaxHelp Twitter feed and you’ll see that streaming glitches continue for the DC sequel, specifically the Roku device. description: 25 hidden moments you missed in the MCUSubscribe: http://bit.ly/Subscribe-to-ScreenrantThe Marvel Cinematic Universe is filled to the brim with all sorts of fun connections to the films themselves as well as a ton of comic books that form the bedrock for the films’ wild plotlines. Some of them, like Captain America’s shield showing up in Iron Man and the Infinity Gauntlet showing up in Odin’s Vault, are pretty obvious to most casual fans — but there’s also plenty to pick apart for more hardcore comic book fanatics. title: The Mandalorian: 6 Theories That Could Still Come True In Season 3
tags: The Mandalorian Season 3|Star Wars|Mando|Grogu|Baby Yoda|The Child|Bo-Katan|Ahsoka Tano|Luke Skywalker|Thrawn|Moff Gideon|Disney Plus|Jon Favreau|Dave Filoni|Boba Fett|screenrant|screen rant
description: Breaking down the most likely theories for season 3 of The MandalorianSubscribe: http://bit.ly/Subscribe-to-ScreenrantWith the adventures of Mando and Grogu seemingly at an end, where does the Mandalorian season 3 go from here? The show has almost exclusively revolved around Mando trying to bring The Child back to the Jedi, and during the last two seasons we’ve really come to see their relationship develop into a true father-son dynamic. As a result, it’s understandable that some fans can’t imagine what the show would be like without them together.However, contrary to what some may think, there ARE a number of potential new directions that the show can go. Based on the finale, the most likely direction would involve the retaking of Mandalore with Bo-Katan’s crew, as well as the possible continued Mandalorian civil war between her people as well as the Mando’s faction Death Watch. Along with this, we could get an appearance from the likes of Grand Admiral Thrawn, Sabine Wren, and the potential return of other familiar faces like Boba Fett! title: We don't Destroy our Bibles like Muslims their Qur'ans!
tags: [none]
description: Another claim by roog49 has him say, Since both religions have a history of manuscripts being destroyed by various rulers over time, the politicization of the original concepts cannot be ignored. That is a misconception, and needs an answer.While Christian manuscripts were destroyed in the Edict of Diocletian in 303, they were never destroyed by Christians, but by the Romans. Christians have never destroyed any of their Biblical manuscripts. Why would we?On the other hand Muslims were well known for destroying any Qur'ans which disagreed with their canonical texts, or which became too difficult to retain.Uthman in 652 AD burned all of the Syriana and Iraqi Qur'ans which disagreed with his Quraishi dialect. Then, by the time all of the official 30 Qira'ats Qur'ans were chosen in the 15th century, all of the hundreds of others which disagreed were destroyed. Finally, in 1924 when Mohammed b. ali al Husayni al Haddad chose the Hafs Qira'at as the official canonized text, all the other 29 which were in existence in the high schools of Cairo were taken out by boat and then dumped into the river Nile. So, the habit of destroying manuscripts of one's revelations is not a practice of Christianity, but certainly was of Islam.© Pfander Centre for Apologetics - US, 2020(44,670) friends-by-aleksound-from-filmmusic-io
